\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 2. Methods
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 2.1 Overview
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf0 We produced two national map layers for England. The first is a 10 m resolution map of the current extent of wet woodland-associated tree cover. The second is a 50 m resolution map of environmental suitability for wet woodland establishment, identifying where terrain, soils, wetness and proximity to water are similar to places where wet woodland currently occurs, and providing a national screening layer to support restoration targeting and nature recovery planning.\'a0
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf0 To create the current extent map, we trained a machine-learning model on satellite-derived spectral descriptors (Google AlphaEarth embeddings, which summarise vegetation and land-cover patterns from Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2) combined with LiDAR-derived terrain variables. The model learned to distinguish wet woodland from other tree cover using training labels derived from Forestry England woodland records (sub-compartments, Forestry Commission {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://environment.data.gov.uk/defra/372d84b9-3a98-4a41-9c70-7106bc3f287d/details"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2026}}), filtered using rule-based criteria based on the occurrence of wet woodland indicator species. Model performance was assessed using spatial cross-validation, ensuring that accuracy estimates reflect how well predictions generalise to new geographic areas rather than areas already seen during training.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf4 \strokec4 To build the suitability map we identified the environmental conditions associated with wet woodland using the training locations used for the extent map . We\'a0 then applied these conditions nationally to identify environmentally suitable areas . Both outputs were summarised at the scale of Local Nature Recovery Strategy ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-nature-recovery-strategies-areas-and-responsible-authorities"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 LNRS}}) areas to provide place-based comparisons relevant to regional nature recovery planning. Full details of predictor preparation, label construction, model training, spatial validation, post-processing and suitability modelling are given in Sections 2.2 to 2.7 below.
\f1\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

